DevOps Engineering Case Study Assignment
Addressbook Application – End-to-End CI/CD Pipeline
Tools Required
GitHub
Jenkins
Maven
Ansible
Terraform
Apache Tomcat
Background

TechConnect Pvt. Ltd. manages an internal Addressbook Application used for employee contact management.

Current Problems:

Manual deployment process
Delayed releases
Inconsistent environments
Production outages

Application Details:

Application: Addressbook – Employee Contact Manager
Language: Java 8
Framework: Vaadin
Build Tool: Maven
Packaging: WAR File (addressbook.war)
Server: Apache Tomcat 9
Cloud: AWS (ap-south-1)

GitHub Repository:
https://github.com/akshu20791/addressbook-cicd-project

Phase 1 – Infrastructure Provisioning (Terraform)

Create AWS infrastructure using Terraform.

Requirements:

Provision 2 EC2 instances:
Jenkins Server
Tomcat Server
Create Security Group allowing:
SSH (22)
HTTP/Tomcat (8080)
Use variables for:
Region
AMI ID
Instance Type
Key Pair
Output:
Jenkins Server Public IP
Tomcat Server Public IP
Organize code into:
provider.tf
variables.tf
main.tf
outputs.tf
Phase 2 – Dependency Installation (Ansible)

Install and configure all software using Ansible.

Jenkins Server

Install:

Java 8
Maven
Jenkins

Configure:

Jenkins service enabled at boot
Tomcat Server

Install:

Apache Tomcat 9

Configure:

Dedicated Tomcat user
Tomcat Manager application
Deployment user for Jenkins
Ansible Structure

Roles:

common
jenkins
tomcat

Master Playbook:

site.yml

Requirement:

Playbooks must be idempotent
Phase 3 – Source Control & Collaboration (GitHub)
Fork repository to your GitHub account.
Clone locally.
Implement branching strategy:
Protect master branch
Use feature branches
Use Pull Requests
Branch Protection Rules:
Minimum 1 reviewer approval
No direct pushes
Make code change:
Create feature branch
Push changes
Raise Pull Request
Get approval
Merge
Configure GitHub Webhook:
Trigger Jenkins automatically on push/merge to master
Phase 4 – CI/CD Pipeline Automation (Jenkins)

Create a Declarative Pipeline.

Jenkins Pipeline Stages
Checkout
Build
Unit Test
Package
Deploy to Tomcat
Requirements
Pipeline stored in Jenkinsfile
Jenkinsfile must be inside GitHub repository
Trigger automatically using GitHub Webhook
No manual build required
Credentials

Store securely in Jenkins Credentials:

GitHub Token
Tomcat Password

Do NOT hardcode credentials.

Additional Configuration
Build timeout
Log rotation (keep last 10 builds)
Workspace cleanup after build
Manual approval before deployment
Phase 5 – Application Build (Maven)

Pipeline should execute:

mvn clean
mvn compile
mvn test
mvn package

Requirements:

Generate WAR file:
addressbook.war
Archive WAR artifact in Jenkins
Publish test reports
Fail build if any unit test fails
Phase 6 – Deployment & Validation (Tomcat)

Deploy automatically after:

Successful build
Manual approval

Application URL:

http://<TOMCAT_SERVER_IP>:8080/addressbook

Validation Steps:

Create feature branch.
Make code change.
Raise Pull Request.
Get approval.
Merge to master.
Jenkins triggers automatically.
Build succeeds.
WAR deploys automatically.
Updated application visible in browser.
Deliverables
1. Terraform (15 Marks)
provider.tf
variables.tf
main.tf
outputs.tf
Two EC2 instances provisioned
2. Ansible (15 Marks)
Roles:
common
jenkins
tomcat
Automated installation
3. GitHub (15 Marks)
Forked repository
Feature branch
Approved PR
Branch protection enabled
4. GitHub + Jenkins (10 Marks)
Webhook configured
Auto-triggered Jenkins build evidence
5. Jenkins (25 Marks)
Jenkinsfile
All stages implemented
Credentials secured
Timeout configured
Log rotation configured
Manual approval gate
6. Maven + Jenkins (10 Marks)
Successful build logs
WAR artifact archived
7. Tomcat (10 Marks)

Screenshot showing:

http://<TOMCAT_IP>:8080/addressbook

running successfully

Constraints
Must use:
Terraform
Ansible
GitHub
Jenkins
Maven
Apache Tomcat
No hardcoded credentials
EC2 instances must be created only through Terraform
Software installation must be done only through Ansible
Jenkinsfile must be stored in repository
PR merge should automatically trigger Jenkins
Manual approval before deployment is mandatory 
